[recv] {"type": "message_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Examining class loading issues**\n\nI need to load a class with hidden prefixes and use the same provider class to call getConsole. The child class should implement a public no-arg constructor and use ServiceLoader for instantiation. It needs to return a `ScenarioResult` from the parent class as either a String or a List<String>. I'm wondering about avoiding direct reflection in tests while ensuring dynamic coverage. Also, I need to catch any errors thrown by URLClassLoader, since it might face unsupported functionality.\n\n**Considering exception handling**\n\nI realize that the native code might throw an Exception, like ClassNotFoundException, instead of an Error. The user only mentioned catching Errors for unsupported dynamic class loading, but if native exceptions occur, that could lead to test failures, which might be acceptable depending on the context. Still, I’m wondering if it would be better to avoid dynamic loading in native entirely. Maybe I should also consider catching UnsupportedOperationException to handle these scenarios more gracefully.\n\n**Inspecting classpath in Gradle**\n\nI’m looking into the Gradle Test JVM setup, especially how the java.class.path usually includes only the Gradle worker jar. But it seems like the actual test classpath is loaded by something called InstrumentingVisitableURLClassLoader? I want to inspect this further, but I notice it hasn’t run yet. I’ll need to figure out more about how this all connects and what it means for my setup. It feels a bit tangled, but I’m on it!\n\n**Considering class loading**\n\nI'm thinking about child class loading and whether a parent can load a duplicate service provider. The ServiceLoader can load a provider using Class.forName, which is promising. I wonder if I need static variables in my fake classes—since they're loaded by the child class, each scenario will have separate copies. It seems the implementation can depend on per-instance state, which could be beneficial for my design choices. This is an interesting puzzle!\n\n**Evaluating ConsoleReader functionality**\n\nI’m working on a fake ConsoleReader in JLine. It has some boolean functions, completors, and queues for managing inputs and outputs. I’m realizing that the scenario can't access the fake reader from within the ShellConsole. It can only assert through console operations, like readLine. I can't assert on outputs or the bell feature. Maybe I need a static registry accessible via classes, but that means I'd have to reference the JLine classes at compile time. That's a tricky situation!\n\n**Assessing scenario loading and imports**\n\nI’m considering that the scenario is loaded by a child class. For the v1 scenario, JLine console is hidden, but it looks like both v1 and v2 are imported. I wonder if importing both might fail class resolution for the hidden v2, even if it’s not used. I think it’s better to avoid importing JLine entirely and just use ShellConsole. The assertions can rely on ShellConsole methods like readLine and print. \n\nFor the proxy completor, if addCompletor encounters an issue, it throws AssertionError—oh wait, I remember that tryInvoke captures InvocationTargetException for these calls and returns null, which might not be reliable. But the proxy creation seems covered, and I need to ensure exercise print/println triggers the right methods. A readLine prompt could help with that!\n\n**Evaluating dynamic loading options**\n\nI'm considering how to guard dynamic loading by testing unsupported operations. I realize there’s no need to skip or perform compile/run actions. If the native environment supports ServiceLoader through a standard classloader, it’s possible our URLClassLoader might not load from URLs, indicating unsupported actions. I also have to think about whether the user-code-filter includes test packages, which might affect how we handle loading.", "th