It seems the implementation can depend on per-instance state, which could be beneficial for my design choices. This is an interesting puzzle!\n\n**Evaluating ConsoleReader functionality**\n\nI’m working on a fake ConsoleReader in JLine. It has some boolean functions, completors, and queues for managing inputs and outputs. I’m realizing that the scenario can't access the fake reader from within the ShellConsole. It can only assert through console operations, like readLine. I can't assert on outputs or the bell feature. Maybe I need a static registry accessible via classes, but that means I'd have to reference the JLine classes at compile time. That's a tricky situation!\n\n**Assessing scenario loading and imports**\n\nI’m considering that the scenario is loaded by a child class. For the v1 scenario, JLine console is hidden, but it looks like both v1 and v2 are imported. I wonder if importing both might fail class resolution for the hidden v2, even if it’s not used. I think it’s better to avoid importing JLine entirely and just use ShellConsole. The assertions can rely on ShellConsole methods like readLine and print. \n\nFor the proxy completor, if addCompletor encounters an issue, it throws AssertionError—oh wait, I remember that tryInvoke captures InvocationTargetException for these calls and returns null, which might not be reliable. But the proxy creation seems covered, and I need to ensure exercise print/println triggers the right methods. A readLine prompt could help with that!\n\n**Evaluating dynamic loading options**\n\nI'm considering how to guard dynamic loading by testing unsupported operations. I realize there’s no need to skip or perform compile/run actions. If the native environment supports ServiceLoader through a standard classloader, it’s possible our URLClassLoader might not load from URLs, indicating unsupported actions. I also have to think about whether the user-code-filter includes test packages, which might affect how we handle loading.", "think